<TITLE> Saudi Crown Prince in Geneva for medical tests </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 RIYADH, April 28 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Crown Prince Sultan of Saudi Arabia, the world's largest oil exporter, has arrived in Switzerland for unspecified medical tests, the official Saudi Press Agency (SPA) reported on Monday. The crown prince, thought to be in his early 80s, arrived in Geneva on Sunday evening with a large retinue for "regular medical tests", SPA said without giving more details. The crown prince had an intestinal cyst removed in Saudi Arabia in 2005 and diplomats say he is in weaker health than King Abdullah, who is thought to be in his mid-80s. He visited Morocco earlier this month for a holiday, Saudi media said. Saudi Arabia, a key US ally, is an absolute monarchy ruled by the Al Saud family with no political parties or elected parliament. There is no designated second-in-line to the throne. Al Qaeda-linked militants launched a violent campaign to destabilise the kingdom in 2003 but it appears to have been brought under control through a tough security crackdow
